<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIGNS OF THE TIMES LOOK BAD FOR FANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Last night, my 7-year-old son came home from the baseball game bursting with 
pride because he witnessed Jose Canseco's back-to-back home runs. However, this 
morning I had to explain to him that we could not go to the autograph signing 
of Jose and other sports figures because of the exorbitant sums of money being 
charged. 
</P>
<P>
No, the money does not go to charity or to help any worthy organizations. It 
goes into the pockets of Jose Canseco, Rickey Henderson and Steve Garvey. 
</P>
<P>
It used to be that an autograph was an act of kindness, a social responsibility 
toward kids who worshiped them. Now it is a commodity and might as well be 
listed with pork bellies on the exchange. 
</P>
<P>
SARA HAZLEWOOD 
</P>
<P>
Orange 
</P>
