<HEADLINE>
<P>
REACTIONS TO THE FALL OF 'MISS SAIGON' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A generation ago, the Rev. Marin Luther King Jr. called on the world not to 
judge individuals by the color of their skin but by the contents of their 
minds. Ironically, the success of the civil rights movement in redressing 
discrimination has created an environment of color consciousness in which an 
individual is pegged into a specific racial or ethnic category. 
</P>
<P>
We have become so fixated with color that we jump to the conclusion that 
because a person is of a certain race, he or she possesses attributes of that 
race and cannot break through the genetic traits. We discount the contents of a 
person's mind. 
</P>
<P>
In essence, we deny the humanity we all share by focusing on superficial 
aspects. We become hostages of tokenism. 
</P>
<P>
More faith should be placed in the possibility that people from different 
backgrounds and ethnicities can empathize and portray each other on the stage. 
If we lose this faith, we will have lost much of the promise of a society that 
once aspired to treat every individual equally without regard to race, creed 
and color. 
</P>
<P>
ALEX ALBEN 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
