<HEADLINE>
<P>
MUSLIMS CONDEMN KUWAIT INVASION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Islamic Center of Southern California condemned the Iraqi invasion of 
Kuwait this week as "alien" to Muslim principles. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Maher Hathout, spokesman for the center, said Iraq may couch its goals in 
religious language but "there is no Islam in that mess. The Islamic stand, as 
stated in the Koran, is quite clear that disputes should not be solved by 
violence." 
</P>
<P>
Salam Al-Marayati, spokesman for the Muslim Political Action Committee in Los 
Angeles, said, "It is a very common tactic in the Muslim Middle East for 
dictators to exploit Islam to maintain power." 
</P>
<P>
In New York, Mohammed T. Mehdi, Iraqi-born president of the National Council on 
Islamic Affairs, also condemned the Iraqi invasion as violating Islamic 
principles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
