<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOREMAN IS BURIED ALIVE IN CAVE-IN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PHIL SNEIDERMAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 33-year-old drilling company foreman died Friday when he was buried head 
first after a trench caved in at a hotel construction site in Glendale. 
</P>
<P>
The accident happened moments after the foreman had warned another worker not 
to stand near the edge of the trench because of the potential for a cave-in, a 
drilling company official said. 
</P>
<P>
Only Enrique Ayala's feet were visible when firefighters arrived about 8 a.m. 
to attempt to rescue him, authorities said. Two of the victim's brothers, who 
also work for Malcolm Drilling Co., watched as firefighters spent an hour 
working with shovels, buckets and their hands to free him. 
</P>
<P>
"I was impatient," said Manuel Ayala of Sylmar, who rushed to Glendale after 
hearing of the accident. "I was hoping they'd have more people helping. I 
wanted to help, but they wouldn't let me go near it." 
</P>
<P>
When Enrique Ayala was freed, paramedics administered cardiopulmonary 
resuscitation and rushed him to Glendale Adventist Medical Center. But hospital 
spokeswoman Sandra Wachter-Van said he was dead on arrival. 
</P>
<P>
A company spokesman said Ayala, of Pacoima, was worried about another worker's 
safety at the time of the accident at 100 W. Glenoaks Blvd. 
</P>
<P>
"Ayala was explaining to a laborer not to stand near the edge of the hole 
because of a possibility of a cave-in," said Shah Arfania, controller of 
Malcolm Drilling. "He was directing the laborer away from that area. The next 
thing that happened is that the hole caved in and Enrique fell in head-first, 
with the rubble and dirt on top." 
</P>
<P>
Arfania said the crew had just used an auger to dig 15 feet down, creating a 
trench that would be filled with concrete to anchor the $36-million, 18-story 
Red Lion hotel. The cave-in occurred before a pipe could be lowered to secure 
the sides of the trench. 
</P>
<P>
The victim's younger brother, Phillip Ayala, 24, who is employed at the 
Glendale site, said he and other workers immediately tried to free the foreman 
but were unsuccessful. "It was really packed tight," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Glendale Fire Capt. Steve Wood said firefighters decided not to use a crane or 
power tools because they feared they would further injure Ayala or destroy any 
air pocket that might be sustaining him. Wood said he understood the impatience 
of onlookers. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a very frustrating type of rescue because it has to be slow and 
meticulous and very deliberate so as not to do any further harm to the 
individual in the hole," Wood said. "You also had to be concerned about any 
second collapse." 
</P>
<P>
After the incident, the job site was shut down for the day. The California 
Division of Occupational Safety and Health and the Los Angeles County district 
attorney's office were investigating. 
</P>
<P>
Cal/OSHA spokesman Rick Rice said his agency has received no previous 
complaints about the Glendale job site. Records of any recent violations by 
Malcolm Drilling were not available Friday, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Malcolm spokesman Arfania said Friday's incident was his company's first 
cave-in death since the firm was founded in 1962. He said Ayala had worked for 
the firm since 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
INDUSTRIAL ACCIDENTS -- LOS ANGELES COUNTY; MALCOLM DRILLING CO; BUILDING 
INDUSTRY -- LOS ANGELES COUNTY 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA081190-0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 260323 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 11, 1990, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 3; Column 6; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
330 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOTHER KILLED; BOY, 2, LEFT IN CAR WITH CASH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PENELOPE McMILLAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At first they seemed separate incidents, half a day and more than 60 miles 
apart. 
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, residents of a Downey neighborhood alerted police that a little 
boy had been found abandoned inside a blue Toyota Cressida parked on their 
street. When Downey police took the 2-year-old into protective custody, they 
quickly realized this was not a typical child-abandonment case. Concealed 
inside the car's trunk was $149,780 in cash. 
</P>
<P>
Shortly before midnight the previous evening, Riverside County sheriff's 
deputies in Hemet had been called to a deserted area near Gilman Hot Springs. 
There they found a 47-year-old Latina, severely beaten. She had crawled to a 
roadway seeking help. Not far away, another Latina, 24, lay dead of a gunshot 
wound. 
</P>
<P>
It took several hours before officials realized the tragic connection between 
the abandoned 2-year-old and the slaying scene. The toddler, identified as Jose 
David, was the son of the dead woman, Claudia Ochoa of Costa Mesa. 
</P>
<P>
"The boy's mother and a family friend were kidnaped Wednesday night," Downey 
Police Chief D. Clayton Mayes said Friday. He said Ochoa's 1984 Toyota was left 
behind in Downey with the child inside when two abductors, identified as Latino 
men, took the women away in a dirty light blue van with no windows. 
</P>
<P>
According to the Riverside Sheriff's office, the women were taken to a location 
near Hemet, where Ochoa was killed. The 47-year-old survivor of the incident, 
whose name has not been made public, was "beaten in the head with a blunt 
instrument," according to police. She underwent surgery at an unidentified 
hospital, and her condition was not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
"The investigation is continuing as to the identity of the suspects, the motive 
for the apparent execution-style murder, and the reason the vehicle and toddler 
were abandoned in Downey," Mayes said. 
</P>
<P>
However, because of the amount of cash discovered in the Toyota's trunk, Mayes 
said detectives believe the incident was drug-related. 
</P>
</TEXT>
