<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHARGERS NOW FIND OUT: SHOULD HE STAY, OR SHOULD HE GO? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CURT HOLBREICH, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chargers open their four-game exhibition season tonight against the Dallas 
Cowboys with a simple mandate: Find out who can play and who can't. 
</P>
<P>
If the philosophy sounds basic, it is. But it isn't easy. 
</P>
<P>
Talent evaluation is a tricky part of NFL life, and with 80 players still in 
camp, this is the time of year it can be most complicated. 
</P>
<P>
And it could be particularly so for the Chargers, a team with more new faces 
than most. In addition to the usual collection of free agents, many of whom 
were originally brought in as little more than warm bodies to fill out training 
camp practices, there are quite a few more expensive newcomers. 
</P>
<P>
Primary among these are the team's nine veteran Plan B free agents, plus 16 
draft choices out of a class of 17, largest in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
These are the players to which the Chargers will be paying careful attention in 
the exhibition against the Cowboys beginning at 7 p.m. at San Diego Jack Murphy 
Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
"We've determined that of the new players, there are some people we really feel 
have a chance to make this team and be productive for us," Coach Dan Henning 
said. "We're not going to evaluate the guys in this game on what they think 
they can do, or what we think they can do. We're going to evaluate them on what 
they do. 
</P>
<P>
"You pick them for potential, but you play them by performance. That is the 
only way you can tell." 
</P>
<P>
The best way is in a game. And after three weeks of practice, including 
controlled scrimmages against the Rams and Phoenix Cardinals, that is what the 
Chargers will do tonight against a team that is coming off a 1-15 season, the 
Cowboys' worst since they were 0-11-1 in their debut year of 1960. 
</P>
<P>
That led to a talent turnover that rivaled any in the league. The Cowboys were 
the most active NFL team in the Plan B market, signing 15 players. They also 
tried to boost their offense in the draft, taking running back Emmitt Smith of 
Florida in the first round and wide receiver Alexander Wright of Auburn in the 
second. The only problem now is that both are unsigned and will not play. 
</P>
<P>
The Cowboys do have quarterback Troy Aikman, back for his second high-paid 
season and saying he is more comfortable than last year. 
</P>
<P>
"Last year, everyone was more curious about what was going to happen," Aikman 
said. "This year, I can just go out and be myself." 
</P>
<P>
The Chargers are looking for much the same from Billy Joe Tolliver, their 
second-year quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
Tolliver had a rough time last week in the scrimmage against the Cardinals, 
throwing two interceptions. This game will continue his NFL education. While 
Henning is using the game to evaluate several new players, he also is laying 
groundwork for the season opener against the Cowboys in Dallas Sept. 9. Maybe 
nowhere is this more important than at quarterback, where the Chargers consider 
themselves talented, but where they clearly are inexperienced. 
</P>
<P>
Tolliver will be making only his seventh NFL start of any kind. But even that 
little bit of game action almost qualifies him as seasoned veteran compared to 
his backups. 
</P>
<P>
Tolliver will be followed by Mark Vlasic, who played in only three games in his 
first three seasons and missed last year because of knee surgery, and John 
Friesz, a sixth-round draft choice from Idaho making his debut in live NFL 
contact situation. 
</P>
<P>
Henning said Tolliver will take about half the snaps, with Vlasic and Friesz 
splitting the other half. That does not necessarily mean Tolliver will not play 
in the second half, Henning said. 
</P>
<P>
"What if we get only five snaps in the second quarter?" he asked. 
</P>
<P>
Presumably, Tolliver then would also play after halftime. Henning has left that 
option open. There are a number of other things he wants to see tonight as 
well. 
</P>
<P>
It's that time of year. 
</P>
<P>
Charger Notes 
</P>
<P>
The game will shown in San Diego on a taped basis on Ch. 10 at 3 p.m. Sunday. 
The radio broadcast will be live on XTRA-AM (690). . . . Tight end Andy Parker 
has two loose teeth and 12 stitches in his lip as the result of an altercation 
in Thursday's practice with linebacker Cedric Figaro on a punt coverage drill 
and will not play, Coach Dan Henning said. Henning said he expected also to 
hold out tight end Arthur Cox (back) and that running back Ronnie Harmon 
(dislocated finger), H-back Joe Caravello (coming back from knee surgery), 
defensive end Burt Grossman (shoulder) and nose tackle Joe Phillips (knee) 
likely will play sparingly. Sure to be missing are linebackers Leslie O'Neal 
and Junior Seau, the team's two remaining contract holdouts. . . . Fuad Reveiz 
and John Carney will alternate kicking duties, and John Kidd and Keith English 
will trade off the punting, Henning said. . . . Henning on wide receiver Nate 
Lewis, a seventh-round draft choice from Oregon Tech: "Nate practiced better 
against Phoenix than he played in the scrimmage (last week). That has got to be 
reversed. Not to the point where I want him to practice poorly, but the object 
is to play well in the game." . . . The Cowboys will stay on in San Diego for 
joint practices with Chargers Monday and Tuesday at UC San Diego. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<CORRECTION-DATE>
<P>
August 12, 1990, Sunday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</CORRECTION-DATE>
